Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
            vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel (standard MVVM):**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **`OnStopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **`OnDestroying`** | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` entirely |
| Restore in **`OnResumed`** | Fires when returning from background |
| Use **`Preferences`** | Fast key-value store; keeps handlers under the ~5s ANR limit |
| Don't use `OnDeactivated` | That fires for dialogs/notification shade — the app may not actually background |
| `OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch | Load initial state in your VM constructor or `OnActivated` if needed |

This pattern keeps your handlers fast and covers all the edge cases across Android, iOS, and Windows.
